aVOr they're responding to requests and concerns
p59
aVby governments that have no jurisdiction
p60
aVover many, or most, of the users and viewers
p61
aVwho are interacting with the content in question.
p62
aa(lp63
VSo here's the situation.
p64
aVIn a pre-Internet world,
p65
aVsovereignty over our physical freedoms,
p66
aVor lack thereof,
p67
aVwas controlled almost entirely
p68
aVby nation-states.
p69
aVBut now we have this new layer
p70
aVof private sovereignty
p71
aVin cyberspace.
p72
aVAnd their decisions about software coding,
p73
aVengineering, design, terms of service
p74
aVall act as a kind of law
p75
aVthat shapes what we can and cannot do with our digital lives.
p76
aVAnd their sovereignties,
p77
aVcross-cutting, globally interlinked,
p78
aVcan in some ways
p79
aVchallenge the sovereignties of nation-states
p80
aVin very exciting ways,
p81
aVbut sometimes also act
p82
aVto project and extend it
p83
aVat a time when control
p84
aVover what people can and cannot do
p85
aVwith information
p86
aVhas more effect than ever
p87
aVon the exercise of power
p88
aVin our physical world.
p89
aVAfter all, even the leader of the free world
p90
aVneeds a little help from the sultan of Facebookistan
p91
aVif he wants to get reelected next year.
